9:T6bd,<p>Systems thinking is the practice of understanding how things influence each other within a whole, rather than analyzing each component in isolation.</p>
<h2>Core insight</h2>
<p>Every complex outcome is the result of a system — a set of elements, interconnections, and a function or purpose. To change outcomes, you usually need to change the system, not just the elements.</p>
<h2>Key concepts</h2>
<p><strong>Feedback loops</strong> — Outputs become inputs. This is how systems self-regulate (or spiral out of control). Reinforcing loops amplify change. Balancing loops resist change.</p>
<p><strong>Delays</strong> — There's almost always a gap between action and result. This is the source of most overshooting and undershooting. When you don't account for delays, you intervene too hard, too late.</p>
<p><strong>Leverage points</strong> — Places in a system where small interventions produce large changes. The highest leverage is usually at the level of goals, information flows, and rules — not at the level of individual components.</p>
<p><strong>Stocks and flows</strong> — Stocks are the quantities in a system (people, money, knowledge). Flows are what changes the stocks (births/deaths, revenue/costs, learning/forgetting).</p>
<h2>Why it matters for building</h2>
<p>Most problems that look like people problems are actually system problems. The individual is behaving rationally given the incentives and information available to them.</p>
<p>If you fix the person but not the system, the system will produce the same behavior through the next person.</p>
<p>Related: <a href="/notes/mental-models" class="wikilink">Mental Models</a>, <a href="/notes/leverage" class="wikilink">Leverage</a></p>
